Summary¶

The first objective of the project is to classify income levels based on a customer's age, gender, and income using two supervised models: K-Nearest Neighbors and Naive Bayes. The second objective is to cluster annual income and spending score with unsupervised models k-means and agglomerative clustering.

g = sns.displot(mall.spending_score, kde=True, bins = 10)

mean_val = np.mean(mall.spending_score)
median_val = np.median(mall.spending_score)
mode_val = mall.spending_score.mode()[0]
skewness = skew(mall.spending_score)
kurt = kurtosis(mall.spending_score)

for ax in g.axes.flat:
    ax.axvline(mean_val, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: {mean_val:.2f}')
    ax.axvline(median_val, color='blue', linestyle='-.', label=f'Median: {median_val:.2f}')
    ax.axvline(mode_val, color='green', linestyle='-.', label=f'Median: {mode_val:.2f}')
ax.legend()

# Print skewness and kurtosis
print(f"Skewness: {skewness:.2f}")
print(f"Kurtosis: {kurt:.2f}")

plt.figure()
stats.probplot(mall.spending_score, dist="norm", plot=plt)
plt.title("Q-Q Plot")
plt.show()

Skewness: -0.05
Kurtosis: -0.84

Hah. This is a strange spread of values. The spending scores are distributed in clusters rather than a normal distribution.
The funny part is the clusters nearly cancel each other out. The skew value is nearly 0 because the clusters at the right and left edges perfectly balance each other. And then its also kinda flat but has the peak in the middle of the flat parts.
Almost like a middle finger.
It's not a very good normal distribution, but it should be good enough to evenly bin the data by quantile.

Supervised Algorithms¶

We're using two supervised classification algorithms: K-Nearest Neighbors and Naive Bayes.

K-Nearest Neighbors: Classify based on the majority class "near" the data point
Naive Bayes: Predicts the class that has the highest probability given the input features. See Bayes Theorem.

mall.head()

4 Female 31 17 40 low

KNN prep¶

KNN requires numerical input data and it requires scaling of the numerical columns. I'll use one-hot encoding for gender,

In [26]:
# One hot encoding for gender column
mall_knn = pd.get_dummies(mall, columns = ['gender'])

mall_knn['gender_Female'], mall_knn['gender_Male'] =  mall_knn['gender_Female'].astype(int), mall_knn['gender_Male'].astype(int)

KNN time!

In [31]:
# Our training and test sets
X = mall_knn[['gender_Male', 'gender_Female', 'age', 'income']].copy()
y = np.array(mall_knn[['spending_level']].copy()).reshape(len(mall_knn),)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, 
    y, 
    test_size=0.2, 
    random_state = 13,
    stratify = y
)
In [32]:
model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)


y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

classes = spend_map.keys()

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, xticklabels =classes, yticklabels = classes, cmap = 'Blues')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('True Label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Eh. It's okay. I'll use cross_validation to check how well the model performs on different subsets.

In [33]:
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = 5, shuffle = True, random_state = 13)


model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)
scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=cv, scoring = 'accuracy' )

print("Cross-validated scores:", scores)
print(f"Mean accuracy: {scores.mean():.2f}")

Cross-validated scores: [0.7   0.75  0.8   0.675 0.775]
Mean accuracy: 0.74

It's okay. Let's try a GridSearch to see if improving n will help.

In [34]:
param_grid = {
    'n_neighbors': list(range(1,25))
}

grid = GridSearchCV(
    estimator = KNeighborsClassifier(), 
    param_grid = param_grid,
    cv = cv,
    scoring = 'accuracy',
    n_jobs = -1,
    verbose = 2
)

grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best parameters found:", grid.best_params_)
print(f"Best CV Score: {grid.best_score_:.4f}")

accuracy = grid.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

Fitting 5 folds for each of 24 candidates, totalling 120 fits
Best parameters found: {'n_neighbors': 5}
Best CV Score: 0.7562
Accuracy: 0.8000

Naive Bayes¶

I've already scaled and transformed the dataset, so we'll continue to use the same X and y. I'm choosing a Gaussian Naive Bayes because there are two roughly normal features.

In [38]:
model = GaussianNB()

model.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("Test set accuracy:", accuracy)

Test set accuracy: 0.7

It's not too bad straight out of the box. We'll try with GridSearchCV to apply the stratified cross validation from above and to test different values for the GaussianNB parameter: var_smoothing.

In [39]:

Agglomerative Clustering¶

Agglomerative Clustering is a type of Hierarchical Clustering, which is a type of clustering that links a dataset by a measure of similarity. Agglomerative just means that the algorithm starts with a cluster for each datapoint and starts linking them. The 2nd type of Hierarchical Clustering called Partial Clustering, starts with one cluster and breaks it into smaller and smaller clusters based on the similarity between points. This will do exactly the same as kmeans but in a different way.

I'm going to use the mall_kmeans dataframe again, and the same X I built in KMeans.

This actually looks pretty close to the first K-Means cluster. And apparently sklearn doesn't have a pipeline to test parameters like GridSearchCV.

There are many parameters I can adjust when using the agglomeratrive clustering function. I'll create a loop to evaluate the models based on n_clusters (number of clusters to produce), linkage method (how to connect clusters), and affinity metric (how distance is measured b/w points).

Now, we'll use the silhouette metric to measure the model. Silhouette is a measure of how close the points are to each other in a cluster and how far they are from the nearest cluster.

In [74]:
linkage_method = ['average', 'complete','single']
affinity_metric = ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'cosine']
sils = []

for k in range(2,11):
    for link in linkage_method:
        for affinity in affinity_metric:
            model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k, linkage=link, metric = affinity)
            labels = model.fit_predict(X)
            score = silhouette_score(X, labels)
            sils.append({
                    'linkage': link,
                    'affinity': affinity,
                    'n_clusters': k,
                    'silhouette': score
                })

for k in range(2,11):
    model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k, linkage='ward', metric = 'euclidean')
    labels = model.fit_predict(X)
    score = silhouette_score(X, labels)
    sils.append({
                    'linkage': 'ward',
                    'affinity': 'euclidean',
                    'n_clusters': k,
                    'silhouette': score
                })
